                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d445">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/3394: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Tientsin</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Fuller</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tientsin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-07-17T16:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 17, 1920—4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 17—9:56 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Referring to my telegram of July 16, 7 p.m. Both of the opposing parties express
                    willingness to permit passenger trains. Train leaves here for Peking this
                    evening. Telegraphic communication is reopened via Mukden. … Chihli troops
                    repulsed yesterday at Yangtsun have been heavily reenforced today. Order is
                    being maintained in Tientsin.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Fuller</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
